'''New Electricity Trading Arrangements''' (NETA) is the system of market trading arrangements under which electricity is traded in the United Kingdom's wholesale [[electricity market]] as of 27 March 2001.<ref>[https://www.ofgem.gov.uk/ofgem-publications/78886/review-first-year-neta-review-document-vol-1.pdf The review of the first year of NETA. A review document: Volume 1]. [[Office of Gas and Electricity Markets|Ofgem]]. July 2002</ref><ref>[https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm200304/cmselect/cmpubacc/63/63.pdf The new electricity trading arrangements in England and Wales - Second Report of Session 2003–04]. House of Commons Committee of Public Accounts, 16 December 2003</ref> The arrangements provided that parties could trade off their [[Load balancing (electrical power)|imbalances]] close to real time.
==BETTA== As of April 2005, NETA changed its name to the British Electricity Trading Transmission Arrangements, and expanding to become the single Great Britain electricity market of England, Wales and Scotland.<ref>[http://www.ofgem.gov.uk/Networks/Trans/Betta/Pages/BETTAarchive.aspx Ofgem archive on BETTA]</ref>
